   <h1>Re: [T2] Interior options</h1>
   <b>"Sherri D. Paxton" <Sherri(-at-)screamingdaisies.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-04-28 04:04:25+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>Rik wrote:

> At 08:32 AM 4/25/2002 -0700, you wrote:
> >I'm planning on turning my '78 Bus into a camper and I was wondering if
> >there are any reference materials, books, magazines on the types of
> >options available? Can I buy after-market option or do I just cannibalize
> >old buses and make it fit?
>
> I suggest you do your own thing.  Use some stock Westy stuff, make some things,
> and use some over the counter things that never came stock.  Unless of
> course, you
> can afford that English camper interior you've been told about.  Nice!
>
> Well, personally, I've got a stock '70 Westy, and the layout isn't all that
> great.
> The icebox is tiny, front opening, and basically useless.  The later
> refrigerators,
> so I've heard endlessly, are nothing but trouble.  Following Bob Hoover's
> advice
> (he hangs out for weeks down in Baja) I got a super-insulated Igloo
> cooler--not the
> un-insulated sort available everywhere.  The cooler can now be taken out of
> the bus,
> as well as used as a seat (with appropriate sized cushion) at the table.
>
> The rear facing seat (on a '70) is slightly too small for a porta-potty, so
> I'm going to
> make a near duplicate that isn't.
>
> Curtains are better held in place with rare earth magnets sown into the seams,
> than the stock aluminum tracks with little plastic thingees sliding in
> them, and snaps.
>
> The stock things I'd use are the folding bed with storage underneath (or a
> Z-bed),
> the folding table, and the shelf above the bed.  If your passenger seat
> swivels around
> to face the rear, as the later Westies did, then use the later style table
> to take advantage
> of this seat.  If not, then use the early table position, and put an early
> loaf sink/water supply/
> ice cooler cabinet behind the passenger seat, but replace the ice cooler
> with storage
> cabinets.  Aside from those, you can really do better going non-stock.
>
> Bob Hoover discussed his thoughts on the matter--he lives in his bus a
> lot--somewhere
> or other in his writings, which you can find here:
>
> http://osf02.ktu.edu.tr/~ulutas/hoover/
>
> Happy trails.
>
> Rik                                                         Searchlight casting
> '70 Westy "The Carcass"                             for faults in the
> ...........be on the road in no time.               clouds of
> delusion.   R. Hunter

Rik,

Thank you very much. I am going to print this message out and keep it to refer to.
I am thinking of building a custom cabinet to house my DVD player and TV which
will reside behind the front drivers seat so I can watch from bed. The DVD is
already set up for 12V but the TV I'm looking at is a standard 13" using regular
110V plug. ( I work for a DVD/TV manufacturer so I have access to  these items). I
have heard of a power inverter but I'm not sure if this is the route I should go
or if I should get a video source already made for automotive applications even
though the screen size is so much smaller.  Any thoughts? I realize I will need an
extra battery but I am getting conflicting opinions from the guys at work on
wether to get a standard battery or a marine battery.

Buster is going into the shop next week to get his mechanicals fixed, after which
I will be looking for interior parts and especially a z bed.

I love the curtain idea. Sounds perfect but does this mean I have to learn to sew?
I knew I should have paid attention in Home Ec. It's pretty sad when a good little
Mormon girl from Utah can't even sew or can peaches! :) I'm sure I can get one of
my friends to do the sewing honors.</pre>


